## Step 3 — Materialise the per-service env files

```bash
test -f "$REPO_ROOT/oci-proxy/oci.dev.env"                       && echo "oci-proxy env EXISTS"   || echo "MISSING"
test -f "$REPO_ROOT/worker/oci.dev.env"                          && echo "worker env EXISTS"       || echo "MISSING"
test -f "$REPO_ROOT/kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.dev.env" && echo "vlm-worker env EXISTS"  || echo "MISSING"
```

If any is missing, copy from its `.tmpl` template:

```bash
cp -n "$REPO_ROOT/oci-proxy/oci.dev.env.tmpl"                      "$REPO_ROOT/oci-proxy/oci.dev.env"
cp -n "$REPO_ROOT/worker/oci.dev.env.tmpl"                          "$REPO_ROOT/worker/oci.dev.env"
cp -n "$REPO_ROOT/kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.dev.env.tmpl" "$REPO_ROOT/kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.dev.env"
```

`-n` ensures we never overwrite an existing local file.

Confirm all three files exist after the copy.

### 3.1 OCI API private key PEM

The `vlm-worker` container needs the user's OCI API private key contents
injected at `docker compose up` time (see Step 5). The PEM file lives at:

```
$REPO_ROOT/kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.oci.key.pem
```

It is **not** a template — the user must place their own key there. Check:

```bash
test -f "$REPO_ROOT/kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.oci.key.pem" \
  && echo "vlm-worker PEM EXISTS" || echo "MISSING — see Step 5 for how to provision"
```

`*.pem` is gitignored in `vsa-control-plane/.gitignore`, so the key cannot
be accidentally committed.

