## Step 4 — Check for REPLACE_ME secrets (without printing values)

```bash
for f in "$REPO_ROOT/oci-proxy/oci.dev.env" \
         "$REPO_ROOT/worker/oci.dev.env" \
         "$REPO_ROOT/kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.dev.env"; do
  if grep -q '^[A-Z_]\+=REPLACE_ME' "$f"; then
    echo "TODO ($f):"
    grep -o '^[A-Z_]\+=REPLACE_ME[^[:space:]]*' "$f" | cut -d= -f1
  fi
done
```

For each key reported, use the **AskQuestion** tool to prompt the user. Do NOT
echo what they type. After the user provides a value, edit the env file in
place with **StrReplace**, replacing the entire `KEY=REPLACE_ME...` line.

Typical keys you'll need to prompt for:
- `OCI_ONTAP_ADMIN_PASSWORD` (oci-proxy + worker) — any non-empty string for
  local dev.
- `ONTAP_CREDENTIAL_ENCRYPT_KEY` on **BOTH** `worker/oci.dev.env` and
  `kubernetes/OCI/vlm-worker/vlm-worker.dev.env` — exactly 32 bytes
  (AES-256). The two values must be **byte-identical**. vcp-worker's
  `clients/vlm/credential_helper.go:17` reads this env var to AES-GCM-encrypt
  ONTAP credentials inside the workflow payload; the vlm-worker container
  decrypts them with the same key. A mismatch (or one side unset) causes
  `vlm.CreateVSAClusterDeploymentWorkflow` to fail at workflow start with
  `illegal base64 data at input byte 0`. If the user wants a throwaway, suggest
  `openssl rand -base64 24 | head -c 32` and let them run it; never generate
  one yourself.
- `VSA_VLM_ENCRYPTION_KEY` (worker only) is a Helm-legacy ConfigMap key
  rendered from the same Helm value but NOT consumed by Go code today.
  Set it to the same 32-byte string as `ONTAP_CREDENTIAL_ENCRYPT_KEY` for
  prod parity, but it does not affect runtime behaviour. **Do not** prompt
  the user for it as a separate value — auto-copy the
  `ONTAP_CREDENTIAL_ENCRYPT_KEY` value into both lines.
- `OCI_TENANCY`, `OCI_USER`, `OCI_FINGERPRINT` (vlm-worker) — the user pulls
  these from their `~/.oci/config` DEFAULT profile. These are identifiers,
  not secrets, but the agent must not log them anyway.
- `OCI_PASSPHRASE` (vlm-worker) — optional. Empty unless the user's
  `vlm-worker.oci.key.pem` is passphrase-encrypted.

### Optional DevFlags (not REPLACE_ME, but commonly toggled)

These are not secrets and have safe code defaults. Mention them on
completion only if the user asks "what else can I tweak":

- `OCI_VSA_EXT_IP_FOR_NODE_MGMT` (worker) — default `false`. When `true`,
  vcp-worker sets `DevFlags.ExtIPForNodeMgmt=true` on every
  `CreateVSAClusterDeploymentRequest`, so VLM provisions an external
  (public) IP on each VSA node's mgmt LIF. Read at
  `core/orchestrator/workflows/oci/pool_workflows.go:45`. Toggle only
  when you actually need to SSH to the VSA over the public internet.
- `OCI_VSA_ALLOW_NON_DENSE_SHAPE_FOR_VSA` (worker) — default `true`. Allows
  non-DenseIO instance shapes for VSA Node VMs. Leave alone unless the
  user explicitly needs to test a DenseIO-only path.

If the user is exercising read-only paths and doesn't have real secrets,
offer to fill them with safe placeholders ("any non-empty string passes
startup validation"). Confirm before doing so. The `vlm-worker` container
will not start without valid OCI identifiers — placeholders work for
`OCI_*` only if the user accepts that no real OCI API calls will succeed.

